# Spring Boot Conventions

Spring is an **infrastructure detail**. Keep the framework at the edges; inner layers stay POJO.

## Dependency injection

- Always use **constructor injection** with `final` fields. Never field injection (`@Autowired` on fields).
- `domain` and `application` classes are plain Java — no Spring annotations.
- Wire use cases (which have no annotations) via `@Bean` methods in `@Configuration` classes
  in `infrastructure` (a per-module `*Config`). Adapters may use `@Component`/`@Repository`.

```java
// infrastructure config wires a framework-free use case
@Configuration
public class UserModuleConfig {
    @Bean
    CreateUserUseCase createUserUseCase(UserRepository repo,
                                        PasswordHasher hasher,
                                        EventPublisher publisher) {
        return new CreateUserUseCase(repo, hasher, publisher);
    }
}
```

## Configuration

- Externalize config in `application.yml`; use profiles (`application-{env}.yml`) per environment.
- Bind config with `@ConfigurationProperties` (typed) over scattered `@Value`.
- Secrets come from environment variables / a secrets manager — never commit them.

## Web & validation

- Enable Jakarta Bean Validation on request DTOs (`@Valid`).
- Use `@RestControllerAdvice` for global error handling (see `presentation.mdc`).

## General

- Keep `NitxRealmApplication` minimal (`@SpringBootApplication` + `main`).
- Prefer constructor-based, testable components; avoid static/global state and the service locator pattern.
- Don't sprinkle `@Transactional` on the domain — apply it at the application/use-case boundary.
